const faq = [
  {
    question: "How do I choose between two npm packages that do similar things?",
    answer: "Consider: (1) Weekly downloads — higher traffic means more real-world testing. (2) GitHub stars — indicates community interest. (3) Last publish date — stale packages may have unpatched vulnerabilities. (4) Bundle size — smaller is better for browser-side code. (5) Maintainer count and issue response time. (6) TypeScript support — does it ship its own types or need @types? (7) License — MIT/Apache for commercial use, check GPL carefully."
  },
  {
    question: "What does 'weekly downloads' indicate?",
    answer: "Weekly downloads from npm show how many times a package was downloaded in the past week. A package with 10M+ weekly downloads is deeply embedded in the ecosystem. However, downloads include CI/CD installs, automated testing, and mirrors — they don't directly equal users. Downloads are better for comparing relative popularity between similar packages than as an absolute quality signal."
  },
  {
    question: "How do I check if a package is actively maintained?",
    answer: "Check: (1) Last publish date on npmjs.com. (2) GitHub commit activity in the last 90 days. (3) Open issues vs closed issues ratio. (4) Whether recent issues get responses. (5) The CHANGELOG — are bugs being fixed? A package can be 'done' and need no updates, or it can be abandoned. Context matters: a utility library with no commits in 2 years may be perfectly stable."
  },
  {
    question: "What license should I look for in npm packages?",
    answer: "MIT and Apache 2.0 are the most permissive and safe for commercial use. BSD is also permissive. ISC is effectively equivalent to MIT. GPL/LGPL requires your project to be open-source if you distribute it — check with your legal team. AGPL is even stricter, covering network use. Unlicensed or 'proprietary' packages should be avoided unless explicitly granted permission."
  },
  {
    question: "Should I prefer a package with more stars or more downloads?",
    answer: "Downloads are a more reliable adoption signal for technical packages. Stars reflect developer interest and marketing, but downloads reflect actual integration into projects. A package with 1K stars but 5M weekly downloads is more widely used than one with 50K stars and 100K downloads. That said, stars correlate with documentation quality and community health."
  }
];

